04375nam a22006855i 9780271075495DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20211993pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710754957 a10.1515/97802710754952doi  a(DE-B1597)584616  a(OCoLC)1280943895  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aDS122.9b.M3 1994 7aREL0400302bisacsh04a956.94/02/0922201 aMarks, Richard G., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Image of Bar Kokhba in Traditional Jewish Literature :bFalse Messiah and National Hero /cRichard G. Marks. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©1993  a1 online resource (244 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHermeneutics: Studies in the History of Religions00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tList of Abbreviations -- tHebrew Transliteration -- tIntroduction: Freedom Fighter, Reckless Thug, Hero-Saint -- t1 Bar Kokhba in Rabbinic Literature -- t2 Bar Kokhba in the Writings of Ibn Daud and Maimonides -- t3 Abravanel's Image of Bar Kokhba -- t4 Bar Kokhba in Sixteenth- Century Historical Writings -- t5 Bar Kokhba in the Later Kabbalah -- tConclusion -- tAppendix: Roman and Christian Writings on the Jewish Rebellion of 116-1 17 and the War of Bar Kokhba -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBar Kokhba led the Jewish rebellion against Rome in 132–135 A.D., which resulted in massive destruction and dislocation of the Jewish populace of Judea. In early rabbinic literature, Bar Kokhba was remembered in two ways: as an imposter claiming to be the Messiah and as a glorious military leader whose successes led Rabbi Akiba, one of the great rabbinic authorities of Jewish tradition, to acclaim him the Messiah. These two earliest images formed the core of most later perceptions of Bar Kokhba, so that he became the prototypical false messiah and the paradigmatic rebel of Jewish history.The Image of Bar Kokhba in Traditional Jewish Literature is a history of the perceptions that later Jewish writers living in the fourth through seventeenth centuries formed of this legendary hero-villain whose actions, in their eyes, had caused enormous suffering and disappointed messianic hopes. Richard Marks examines each writer's account individually and in the context of its period, exploring particularly political and religious implications. He builds a history of images and looks at larger patterns, such as the desacralizing of traditional imagery. His findings raise timely political questions about Bar Kokhba's image among Jews today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aJewish historians. 0aJewsxHistoryyBar Kokhba Rebellion, 132-135xHistoriography. 0aRabbinical literaturexHistory and criticism. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978027107549540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271075495423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271075495/original  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK